<doc id="48634" wikidata="Q1991405" url="?curid=48634" title="Nowhere dense set">
<text>In mathematics, a subset of a topological space is called nowhere dense or rare if its closure has empty interior. In a very loose sense, it is a set whose elements are not tightly clustered (as defined by the topology on the space) anywhere. For example, the integers are nowhere dense among the reals, whereas the interval (0, 1) is not nowhere dense.

A countable union of nowhere dense sets is called a meagre set. Meagre sets play an important role in the formulation of the Baire category theorem, which is used in the proof of several fundamental results of functional analysis.

== Definition ==

Density nowhere can be characterized in different (but equivalent) ways. The simplest definition is the one from density:
A subset formula_1 of a topological space formula_2 is said to be dense in another set formula_3 if the intersection formula_4 is a dense subset of formula_5 formula_1 is &#x27; or &#x27; in formula_2 if formula_1 is not dense in any nonempty open subset formula_3 of formula_10 
Expanding out the negation of density, it is equivalent that each nonempty open set formula_3 contains a nonempty open subset disjoint from formula_12 It suffices to check either condition on a base for the topology on formula_10 In particular, density nowhere in formula_14 is often described as being dense in no open interval.

=== Definition by closure ===

The second definition above is equivalent to requiring that the closure, formula_15 cannot contain any nonempty open set. This is the same as saying that the interior of the closure of formula_1 is empty; that is,formula_17 Alternatively, the complement of the closure formula_18 must be a dense subset of formula_19 in other words, the exterior of formula_1 is dense in formula_10

== Properties ==

The notion of &quot;nowhere dense set&quot; is always relative to a given surrounding space. Suppose formula_22 where formula_23 has the subspace topology induced from formula_10 The set formula_25 may be nowhere dense in formula_26 but not nowhere dense in formula_27 Notably, a set is always dense in its own subspace topology. So if formula_25 is nonempty, it will not be nowhere dense as a subset of itself. However the following results hold:
* If formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_30 then formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_10
* If formula_23 is open in formula_2, then formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_23 if and only if formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_10
* If formula_23 is dense in formula_2, then formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_23 if and only if formula_25 is nowhere dense in formula_10

A set is nowhere dense if and only if its closure is.

Every subset of a nowhere dense set is nowhere dense, and a finite union of nowhere dense sets is nowhere dense. Thus the nowhere dense sets form an ideal of sets, a suitable notion of negligible set. In general they do not form a 𝜎-ideal, as meager sets, which are the countable unions of nowhere dense sets, need not be nowhere dense. For example, the set formula_45 is not nowhere dense in formula_46

The boundary of every open set and of every closed set is closed and nowhere dense. A closed set is nowhere dense if and only if it is equal to its boundary, if and only if it is equal to the boundary of some open set (for example the open set can be taken as the complement of the set). An arbitrary set formula_47 is nowhere dense if and only if it is a subset of the boundary of some open set (for example the open set can be taken as the exterior of formula_25).

== Examples ==

* The set formula_49 and its closure formula_50 are nowhere dense in formula_51 since the closure has empty interior.
* The Cantor set is an uncountable nowhere dense set in formula_46
* formula_14 viewed as the horizontal axis in the Euclidean plane is nowhere dense in formula_54
* formula_55 is nowhere dense in formula_14 but the rationals formula_45 are not (they are dense everywhere).
* formula_58 is nowhere dense in formula_14: it is dense in the open interval formula_60 and in particular the interior of its closure is formula_61
* The empty set is nowhere dense. In a discrete space, the empty set is the nowhere dense set.
* In a T1 space, any singleton set that is not an isolated point is nowhere dense.
* A vector subspace of a topological vector space is either dense or nowhere dense.

== Nowhere dense sets with positive measure ==

A nowhere dense set is not necessarily negligible in every sense. For example, if formula_2 is the unit interval formula_63 not only is it possible to have a dense set of Lebesgue measure zero (such as the set of rationals), but it is also possible to have a nowhere dense set with positive measure. One such example is the Smith–Volterra–Cantor set.

For another example (a variant of the Cantor set), remove from formula_64 all dyadic fractions, i.e. fractions of the form formula_65 in lowest terms for positive integers formula_66 and the intervals around them: formula_67 
Since for each formula_68 this removes intervals adding up to at most formula_69 the nowhere dense set remaining after all such intervals have been removed has measure of at least formula_70 (in fact just over formula_71 because of overlaps) and so in a sense represents the majority of the ambient space formula_72 
This set is nowhere dense, as it is closed and has an empty interior: any interval formula_73 is not contained in the set since the dyadic fractions in formula_73 have been removed.

Generalizing this method, one can construct in the unit interval nowhere dense sets of any measure less than formula_75 although the measure cannot be exactly 1 (because otherwise the complement of its closure would be a nonempty open set with measure zero, which is impossible).

For another simpler example, if formula_3 is any dense open subset of formula_14 having finite Lebesgue measure then formula_78 is necessarily a closed subset of formula_14 having infinite Lebesgue measure that is also nowhere dense in formula_14 (because its topological interior is empty). Such a dense open subset formula_3 of finite Lebesgue measure is commonly constructed when proving that the Lebesgue measure of the rational numbers formula_45 is formula_83 This may be done by choosing any bijection formula_84 (it actually suffices for formula_84 to merely be a surjection) and for every formula_86 letting 
formula_87
(here, the Minkowski sum notation formula_88 was used to simplify the description of the intervals). 
The open subset formula_89 is dense in formula_14 because this is true of its subset formula_45 and its Lebesgue measure is no greater than formula_92 
Taking the union of closed, rather than open, intervals produces the F-subset
formula_93
that satisfies formula_94 Because formula_95 is a subset of the nowhere dense set formula_96 it is also nowhere dense in formula_46 
Because formula_14 is a Baire space, the set
formula_99
is a dense subset of formula_14 (which means that like its subset formula_101 formula_102 cannot possibly be nowhere dense in formula_14) with formula_104 Lebesgue measure that is also a nonmeager subset of formula_14 (that is, formula_102 is of the second category in formula_14), which makes formula_108 a comeager subset of formula_14 whose interior in formula_14 is also empty; however, formula_108 is nowhere dense in formula_14 if and only if its in formula_14 has empty interior. 
The subset formula_45 in this example can be replaced by any countable dense subset of formula_14 and furthermore, even the set formula_14 can be replaced by formula_117 for any integer formula_118

