<doc id="48636" wikidata="Q191690" url="?curid=48636" title="Partition of unity">
<text>In mathematics, a partition of unity of a topological space is a set of continuous functions from to the unit interval [0,1] such that for every point formula_1:
* there is a neighbourhood of where all but a finite number of the functions of are 0, and
* the sum of all the function values at is 1, i.e., formula_2

Partitions of unity are useful because they often allow one to extend local constructions to the whole space. They are also important in the interpolation of data, in signal processing, and the theory of spline functions.

== Existence ==
The existence of partitions of unity assumes two distinct forms:

# Given any open cover formula_3 of a space, there exists a partition formula_4 indexed &quot;over the same set&quot; such that supp formula_5 Such a partition is said to be subordinate to the open cover formula_6
# If the space is locally-compact, given any open cover formula_3 of a space, there exists a partition formula_8 indexed over a possibly distinct index set such that each has compact support and for each , supp formula_9 for some .

Thus one chooses either to have the supports indexed by the open cover, or compact supports. If the space is compact, then there exist partitions satisfying both requirements.

A finite open cover always has a continuous partition of unity subordinated to it, provided the space is locally compact and Hausdorff. 
Paracompactness of the space is a necessary condition to guarantee the existence of a partition of unity subordinate to any open cover. Depending on the category to which the space belongs, it may also be a sufficient condition. The construction uses mollifiers (bump functions), which exist in continuous and smooth manifolds, but not in analytic manifolds. Thus for an open cover of an analytic manifold, an analytic partition of unity subordinate to that open cover generally does not exist. &quot;See&quot; analytic continuation.

If and are partitions of unity for spaces and , respectively, then the set of all pairs formula_10 is a partition of unity for the cartesian product space . The tensor product of functions act as formula_11

== Example ==
We can construct a partition of unity on formula_12 by looking at a chart on the complement of a point formula_13 sending formula_14 to formula_15 with center formula_16. Now, let formula_17 be a bump function on formula_15 defined by formula_19 then, both this function and formula_20 can be extended uniquely onto formula_12 by setting formula_22. Then, the set formula_23 forms a partition of unity over formula_12.

==Variant definitions==
Sometimes a less restrictive definition is used: the sum of all the function values at a particular point is only required to be positive, rather than 1, for each point in the space. However, given such a set of functions formula_25 one can obtain a partition of unity in the strict sense by dividing by the sum; the partition becomes formula_26 where formula_27, which is well defined since at each point only a finite number of terms are nonzero. Even further, some authors drop the requirement that the supports be locally finite, requiring only that formula_28 for all formula_29.

In the field of operator algebras, a partition of unity is composed of projections formula_30. In the case of formula_31-algebras, it can be shown that the entries are pairwise-orthogonal:
formula_32
Note it is &quot;not&quot; the case that in a general *-algebra that the entries of a partition of unity are pairwise-orthogonal.
If formula_33 is a normal element of a unital formula_31-algebra formula_35, and has finite spectrum formula_36, then the projections in the spectral decomposition:
formula_37
form a partition of unity.

In the field of compact quantum groups, the rows and columns of the fundamental representation formula_38 of a quantum permutation group formula_39 form partitions of unity.

==Applications==
A partition of unity can be used to define the integral (with respect to a volume form) of a function defined over a manifold: one first defines the integral of a function whose support is contained in a single coordinate patch of the manifold; then one uses a partition of unity to define the integral of an arbitrary function; finally one shows that the definition is independent of the chosen partition of unity.

A partition of unity can be used to show the existence of a Riemannian metric on an arbitrary manifold.

Method of steepest descent employs a partition of unity to construct asymptotics of integrals.

Linkwitz–Riley filter is an example of practical implementation of partition of unity to separate input signal into two output signals containing only high- or low-frequency components.

The Bernstein polynomials of a fixed degree &quot;m&quot; are a family of &quot;m&quot;+1 linearly independent single-variable polynomials that are a partition of unity for the unit interval formula_40.

The weak Hilbert Nullstellensatz asserts that if formula_41 are polynomials with no common vanishing points in formula_42, then there are polynomials formula_43 with formula_44. That is, formula_45 form a polynomial partition of unity subordinate to the Zariski-open cover formula_46. 

Partitions of unity are used to establish global smooth approximations for Sobolev functions in bounded domains.

